{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_try_except",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Try, Except & Specific Errors",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Instead of letting errors crash your program, you can **catch** them and decide what to do. This is called **exception handling**."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `try` and `except` blocks let your program continue running even when errors occur."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "basic_try_except",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Basic Try and Except",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Put code that might cause an error in a `try` block. If an error happens, Python runs the `except` block instead of crashing."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "try:\n    number = int(\"hello\")\n    print(number)\nexcept:\n    print(\"Oops! That didn't work.\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Oops! That didn't work."
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Python tries to convert the string `\"hello\"` to an integer. Since `\"hello\"` isn't a valid number, it raises an error. The `except` block catches this error and prints a friendly message instead of letting the program crash."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "program_continues",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "With error handling, your program keeps running after an error."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "print(\"Start\")\n\ntry:\n    result = 10 / 0\nexcept:\n    print(\"Can't divide by zero!\")\n\nprint(\"End\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Start\nCan't divide by zero!\nEnd"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Notice that `\"End\"` prints! The program didn't crash - it handled the error and continued."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
