        },
        {
            "id": "specific_errors",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Catching Specific Errors",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Instead of catching all errors, you can catch **specific error types**. This lets you handle different errors differently."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "try:\n    age = int(\"twenty\")\nexcept ValueError:\n    print(\"Please enter a valid number\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Please enter a valid number"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "This only catches `ValueError`. Other errors would still crash the program (which can be useful for debugging)."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "why_specific",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Why catch specific errors?** It makes your error messages more helpful and helps you handle different problems in different ways."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = [10, 20, 30]\n\ntry:\n    print(numbers[5])\nexcept IndexError:\n    print(\"Index doesn't exist in list\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Index doesn't exist in list"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The error message clearly tells the user what went wrong."
                }
            ]
        },
